<user_id>114519554327877171947< /user_id><Name>Nick Carson</Name><time>1559768803634< /time><rating>1< /rating>< Review>
First off, I have been a customer of Sports clips off and on for over five years but today was the last straw.

I was seated at 11:20 and I was walking out of the shop at 11:32!!! I told  Margarita how I wanted my haircut. She immediately started cutting my hair wayyyyy too fast. I told her I wanted a medium fade, skin on the sides and a comb over on top.

She didn't cut the sides short enough and she cut wayyyyy too much off the top. So much that I can't even 'comb it over'.

I paid for a tripple play, because I like the steam towel and my hair washed. She spent literally 2 minutes washing my hair and with the steam towel on.

She went way too fast and the tripple play experience was not the usual experience.

Bad haircut, Margarita was in a hurry and didn't provide good customer service at all. She didn't even talk... YOUR CUSTOMER OF FIVE YEARS WILL NEVER BE COMING BACK.

If you are in the Military, you're better off getting a hair cut at the exchange and we all know how bad those cuts are.

If you want a great haircut I HIGHLY recommend "Tomahawk barbershop" in Ventura those guys will take care of you. There's a reason they have a 5 star review and Sports clips doesn't even have a 4.

Nobody does a quality haircut and wash in 12 minutes.... There's absolutely no reason why an employee should be rushing the customers out the door.<//Review>

<Review>We went to the SF Pet Hospital for over 20 years. We took our older dog Gracie to be seen because she had been experiencing some arthritis in her hips which was being treated after being seen at the SFSPCA (when we called the the Pet Hospital to see her they told us to go somewhere else, they would not fit her in). After I had called her Pet Hospital vet a couple of times to check the meds, Dr. Leyba  got back to me.  We decided to follow up at the Pet Hospital and Dr. Hunter found a mast cell tumor on her side (which I had been concerned about).  She did the surgery on Gracie the following week and left on vacation.  Dr. Hunter has never followed up with us nor checked in on Gracie again.  Ever.

Gracie came home after the surgery that Thursday mildly sedated and given Buprenorphine (an opiate) to be given 2-3x/ day.  My girl never recovered.  I called on the Friday telling the tech (because the vet never returned my call) about her troubles.  She was sedated, not herself.  And the tech told me that I needed to give her Benadryl and an acid regulator.  I called back on Saturday morning, a tech told me Gracie, who paced all night, who was no longer walking, nor eating or  drinking, was "fine."  She never even suggested seeing her.  Again, no vet ever called nor responded.  I called again in the afternoon as Gracie had grown despondent, cold, drooling more and more.  The same tech said Gracie was "milking it" because she was an older dog and that bringing her in would be "too stressful." Gracie died in our home with our children a couple hours later.  The death in our home was horribly traumatic for all of us.  The Pet Hospital, Dr. Leyba and Dr. Hunter and the staff never called to check on Gracie.  After her death, I called and spoke to Dr. Leyba about the mismanagement of her case. Six years ago, we noticed lumps on my malamute. After our current vet said they were only "old dog lumps" we opted for a second opinion with SF Pet Hospital. < text>
I just hanged up the phone with them. I have had my 6 year old Australian shepherd come to this office since she was a puppy.  Fortunately she is an extremely healthy dog and never needed urgent care.  We recently got a puppy and brought her for her vaccinations.  Several times I got conflicting information about the vaccination schedule and was confused because they gave her one more shot of DHHP vaccine than necessary.  When I inquired about it they said the doctor would call me to discuss.  That never happened.  They called me back to charge me for the vaccines and I again asked to speak to the doctor.  Never got a call back.  On Saturday, my now 4 month old puppy that chewed through a bottle of Tylenol and we rushed her to the ER.  She was hospitalized for 48 hours and is still not acting like herself.  The ER recommendation was to see her regular doctor and get one more blood test to make sure she has no liver damage (the past 2 tests were clear).  I called them to make an appointment explaining that the test needs to be given at the 72 hour mark. I am sorry, we don't have availability. Me: can I speak to the doctor please? Them: No, the doctor is in procedures right now and even if you talk to them, that will not change the outcome. We don't have availability. Me: this is an urgent matter, I need to see her regular doctor. Them: sorry, we can't fit you in today. Take her to the ER again. It is clear to me that they don't care about their patients, even the most vulnerable ones. Do yourself a favor and find a veterinarian who actually cares about their patients. This place may have good doctors (the doctors have been great in my experience) but if you can't count on them when it really matters, when your dog is actually in need, then it does not matter how good they are.<//text>

They are very skilled, well-trained and all have excellent communication skills. They never talked down to me or tried to baffle me with medical terminology.  They were also extremely kind and compassionate during my dogs final hours.  He recently passed away from a tumor at the age of 12.  They were incredibly kind and compassionate and helped me make my final decision with confidence.</text>

< Name>
charles chiles<//Name>
<date>1524816166501<//date><rate>5<//rate>< Review>
I would say that Party City - there are a number of different outlets throughout San Diego County - is basically a department store that specializes in selling just about anything that you can imagine, especially when what you want revolves around the purchasing of presents or for staging any festive occasion.
Their plethora of merrymaking merchandise is there, awaiting your own inventiveness and creativity ; either plan the festivities yourself, with a few family members or friends and go for it...
They have supplies/gifts for baby showers, weddings, birthday parties of all ages and all kinds of what-you-may-call-its.
I just went there to browse and I walked out with some dice, a new deck of playing cards, and a small box of crayons.< /Review>

<review>What can I say, we loved our experience here. I was mainly coming for the view expecting ho bum food but we were pleasantly surprised:

Pros:

Staff was SO helpful and friendly. They even brought another heater out by our table to help keep us warm.

Food - we ordered the chicken and shortrib dishes. Short Ribs were so great and the Brussels with the chicken were to die for. Chicken had a nice crispy skin.

Ambiance/vibe: SO great. We came for sunset and looking out at the harbor with charming music piling through the speakers was just perfect. When dark enough their beautiful outdoor lights sparkled on. So charming.

Cons:
Chicken was nothing special and could have benefited from a thicker sauce or stronger flavor

Overall a 5/5< /review>< pics>

<Gmap_id>0x80deab0d284064d9:0xba249d609c190abe<//Gmap_id><user>107680562744832662724<//user><Name>teadrinkerxyz<//Name><rate>5</rate>< text>
Based on a friend‚Äôs recommendation, we came for Sunday brunch for the first time.  We made a 9:45AM reservation and requested a window table.  There was one available when we arrived.  We were seated promptly.  The view was spectacular!  Toward noon, the sun came though the window, so bring your sunglasses.

Service was excellent!   They were very attentive.   My champagne glass was never empty.   The finished plates were promptly taken away.  The buffet food was restocked frequently.   No complain!

Food:  the Maine lobster claws, oysters, cocktail shrimps, crab legs, and scallops were so fresh!  The cooked food and desserts were delicious!  Pasta and omelette station were very inviting.  There was bottomless mimosas (you can mix orange juice and champagne yourself).  We leave the restaurant satisfied.   One word summary:  yummy!<//text>

Even tho I was dining solo, my server never made me feel rushed and took care of me as if I was a party of 10. I will be back every time I am in San Diego! Highly recommended!< /Review>

<user>104734375221286977691< /user><user_name>Stacey Cab</user_name><date>1582753692557<//date><Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
Out of towner that was here for a wedding rehearsal dinner.  GREAT location in downtown San Diego.  Easy to get to, plenty of parking, along with handicap accommodations.

As for the food, it was absolutely fantastic!  From the cheeses, entrees and dessert, everything was tasty!  The wait staff was attentive to our needs and it was a beautiful venue.  It was slightly pricey after looking at the main menu, but it was worth it!  Definitely a must go for view and food!   The view gives you a scenic view of San Diego.</Review>

<review>The views alone are worth checking this place out! At night come for apps and drinks and enjoy a view of the lit up city!

During the day, the harbor is a beautiful backdrop and tons of natural light bathes your table or you can even sit outside on the deck.

The food hasnt blown me away but it's ok! Hubby had a cheese plate that was fine and he shared a seafood platter with some friends. I've tried the ceviche and a cocktail (Saucy Sally) and they were both middle ground. That being said, the view is enough that we plan to go back to try some other plates!</review>< Pics>

The food was just ok. Not anywhere close to the type of taste and quality you would expect for the price. The service was horrible. Our waitress spent her time on the tables on both sides of us to talk very loudly about how much she disliked tourists. When she did actually wait on our table she was not friendly with us at all. We ordered oysters as a starter and ended up getting our salads before the oysters came out. She only acknowledged the error by stating she would put a hold on our entr√©es. Which we later found out that that meant they had already cooked them, however she just didn't bring them to our table right away. Food was barely warm by the time it reached our table. As a place that is a tourist destination with amazing views. You would think the server would have an appreciation for the tourists dollars. Sadly this was not the case.<//review>

< text>
This is a mixed review.  The setting is beautiful. We ate outside on the second level facing downtown, lights, etc.  They didn't honor our reservation for a window table which had been made over a week before.  They gave us a fine dessert for our anniversary.  The service was very good. The food was just OK, especially for the price.  The real negative was the bill which came with a 3% surcharge which was unannounced and not mentioned in the menu. This establishment has hosted wedding receptions within the last two weeks which is NOT allowed under San Diego County policy setforth on Sept 10.
Employees who inform the management of policy are asked to mind their own business.
Restaurants that CANNOT follow the restrictions setforth for the Gen public safety as well as the safety of employees SHOULD NOT be allowed to operate at this time. Shame on the Lighthouse owners for not upholding the standards setforth by family generations before them!!<//Text>

<Review>I have been to Tom Ham's Lighthouse for brunch many times and I am never disappointed.  I leave happy and extremely full.  They have a variety of foods, such as the usual fruit, bacon, sausage and Eggs Benedict.  They also have other items such as fresh salads, meats, cheeses and lox.

However the highlight of my time at Tom Ham's Lighthouse is the Massive Seafood Bar.  This bar contains crab legs, lobster claws, peel and eat shrimp, oysters, scallops and ceviche.  Everything is so fresh and delicious.  The cocktail sauce is amazing and contains the right amount of horseradish.  BOMB!!

Tom Ham's also has a great pasta and omelette station. I recommend taking some of the seafood from the seafood bar, and shucking or shelling it all and taking it the pasta and omelette station to put inside of your pasta or create an egg scramble.

Tom Ham's is amazing and one of my favorite Brunch spots.  They take Walk Ins, but I recommend you make a reservation on Open Table in advance.<//Review><pictures>None</pictures><resp>None</resp>< gmap_id>

1520047517449</Date>
< rating>
3<//rating>
< review>
The major perk of this place: The views, for sure! We ate outside on a sunny afternoon and the building blocked the winds, so we were quite comfortable! Our server was very nice and even cracked a few jokes.

I had to give it 3 stars though because the food was just meh. It costs >$50 a person to have an all you can eat buffet that isn't that good. We started out with the seafood--lobster, crab, oyster, scallop--and it was bland, didn't taste fresh or interesting, and none of us went back for seconds. I went for the eggs benedict next, and also found it bland. I guess my favorite dishes were the bread budding and the french toast, but I can get those things for much cheaper elsewhere.

For the view it's almost worth it, but I wouldn't recommend it ultimately unless $50 doesn't mean much to you.</review>

< review>
I took my wife here for our wedding anniversary.  I was looking for a place on the water, with a view, has outdoor seating, good seafood and oysters.  Tom Ham's fit the bill.  Beautiful view of the SD skyline, Coronado and tons of boats out on a warm summer evening.  They had 7 varieties of oysters on the menu, we tried 5.  All delicious.  I got the whole fish which was rockfish for the evening.  Normally I don't go for rockfish but I've never been disappointed with the whole fish and this was no exception.  I really couldn't get over how good it was and how perfectly it was prepared.  Tom Ham's wasn't on the top of my search results, but I'm glad I found them and gave them a try.  Oh, and the wait staff (sorry sir, but I forgot your name) was professional, polite, knowledgeable and right on top of everything.  It was the perfect evening.<//review>

< text>
My future husband and I LOVE Tom Ham's. We booked it for our wedding in July and keep coming back in the mean time for the epic food and awesome beer choices, plus the view and friendly staff (thanks for making TH's our second home Tim, Joe, Ian and Michelle!). Their 30ish beer taps change constantly and they have a great selection of SD and other craft beers. The happy hour has great deals on the food and drink, and $1 oysters. The regular menu is pricey, but the food is top notch and delicious. Plus the view.</text>

< user_name>
Angel Ramos</user_name>
<Resp>None< /Resp>< Text>
This place was amazing!! Definately has a lot of class, style and the sunset views of the city was beautiful.

My lovely lady took me to this restaurant for my birthday, it was the best possible location she could have reserved.

The food was amazing, i had an entre i can't even pronounce lol but it was the only one with lobster i believe. The lobster was delicious and the sauce really topped off the taste and flavors. It came with 2 sliced tosted breads to dip, scallops and clams. I am probably not doing the dish any service with my limited description but I'm not a chef so trust me when i say, their food is more than worth it.

The customer service was exceptional, the server knew everything about their dishes and had a very well creative and articulate manner in how to describe it to us. The wine was really good but maybe i could have chosen a white wine for my dish, i don't do white wine much.

Their dessert was delectable and just the right amount after a full entre. I had a cream brulee if that's the way you spell it, otherwise, my mistake, i don't feel like googling it or spell checking right now.

The view was really nice, when the sun is up you can see the ocean and the sailboats up close just underneath the patio or balcony seating. When the sun sets, you get beautiful views of the San Diego skyline. It is a great place for photos with a loved one, family or friends after your meal.

The food came out in a timely manner and the whole experience felt like this restaurant runs like a well oiled machine. I can't see why anyone would care to give them anything less than a 5 star.

I'd love to keep rambling on about this place but i got to work. Definately recommend it to anyone.<//Text>

< Text>
My fiance and I checked out this place as we had an appointment scheduled for a possible wedding venue. The coordinator we met with very was very professional and courteous, answered all our questions and showed us around. We loved the views the venue has (Coronado and downtown SD) and loved how quiet the place is deposited being close proximity to the airport. We decided to try lunch after our appointment and the food was just as amazing. We split the white cheddar burger, cooked perfect medium and the fish and chips. Excellent flavor and just the right crispiness. We decided to use this venue as our choice for our wedding and do not regret the decision.</Text>

<Resp>None<//Resp><Date>1570468211880<//Date>< Pics>

<Gmap_id>0x80deab0d284064d9:0xba249d609c190abe<//Gmap_id><rating>5</rating><userid>113688595179567981693</userid><username>Zachary Steele</username>< text>
Went here the other night and was beyond impressed. It has such a great and unique atmosphere. Most times with upscale restaurants like this you are left paying an absurd price for delicious food but incredibly small portions. Tom Ham's is definitely different in this regard, as the portions they give you are plentiful at prices that are absolutely reasonable for how well prepared the food is. I was also blown away by the prices of the cocktails for how good they were. The Bali Hai Mai Tai doesn't disappoint and the other drinks we had were fantastic while not being overpriced in the slightest. Also, contrary to other reviews on here, they do go out of their way to celebrate birthdays and are willing to go the extra mile to make that night special (cake and special seating with a great view for no extra charge). Perhaps this was a reflection of the server we had (who was wonderful), but every employee who we spoke with that night was also incredibly accommodating and friendly, so I don't think it was limited to that individual.

This is definitely one of the best spots in all of San Diego and I will absolutely be coming back for more of that asparagus and more drinks in the future! Can't say enough great things about this place!<//text>

< text>
I went with a couple of friends for restaurant week. We all ordered something different so we could sample a good amount of the items on their pre fixe menu, which is actually quite large. We tried the beer salad, crudo & steak bites all were quite good & good sized portions. For entree's we did the pan seared duck, scallops & the shrimp pasta, again all were really fantastic & good sized portions. The dessert course we had cheese cake, creme brulee & apple crumb cake. Overall I couldn't be happier with this amazing meal. Highly recommended!</text>

<date>1560203035763</date>< Rating>

< Text>
Recently hosted a luncheon there for about 30 people and reserved the upstairs private room.  Luz, our coordinator, took care of everything and everything was perfect - right down to our custom signage downstairs and personalized menus, neither of which were expected.  Our servers Sarah and Molly were on top of everything and helped us with some last minute changes (vases for flowers we brought, etc.) and volunteered to take our picture at the end in a beautiful spot with a perfect view.  The food all came out quickly and all at once and was all delicious.
I have been going to Tom Ham's Lighthouse for years and will now certainly keep them in mind for any event I need to host.
Oh .. and not to mention, I came in well under budget for my event.  5 stars for the whole encounter !!</Text>

< review>
I came here to indulge in the 3-course special during restaurant week.  A really good deal for only $35! The restaurant is in a great location on Harbor Island, with beautiful views of the downtown skyline just right across the bay.  We grabbed some outside seating so we can enjoy the view while the sunset reflecting beautifully from the buildings of the skyline. So pretty!! :)

The service was great.  The hosts were nice but our server was even sweeter.  He was very informative about their specials and raw bar menu.  For appetizers, my friend and I got calamari and mussels and both were delicious! For the main course, I enjoyed the clam linguine and my friend got the paella which she enjoyed just as much.  The desserts were a little tiny, but they were both really delicious and the perfect amount of sweetness.  I will consider going again :)  It was a great place for seafood.</review>

<user_id>104219722876783340853< /user_id>< user_name>
Wendy Murphy< /user_name>
<Date>1470252078975< /Date>< rating>
3</rating>
< text>
Waterfront restaurant with magnificent views. I can imagine this would be a great place for a wedding or other big event. Waitstaff was friendly, if a bit on the slow side. We waited forever for our desserts and coffee, as well as the bill.Prices are what you would expect to pay at a semi-fancy waterfront restaurant in San Diego. If you want a burger for dinner, you will want to look somewhere else!
We were a party of 8 so there was a lot of different dishes ordered. Calamari and a platter of muscles was devoured quickly for starters.Two people had the Kobe steak which was good, but I have definitely had a much better steak at numerous (and less expensive) restaurants. Another had the Prime NY and it was tasty, if a bit on the small size for the price. The yellow tail and pan seared salmon were enjoyable and well seasoned. The bouillabaisse was a hit, as was the paella.
Key lime pie and a couple of hard rootbeer floats finished things off in a tasty and sweet way. The fact that anyone had room for dessert (very unusual for this group!) may give you an idea of the portion sizes of the dinner selections.
All in all I would say it was good. Expensive, but good. The real star of the night was the view, which was fantastic. So if you are looking for atmosphere to be the star, this is a good choice. If you want the food to be the main attraction, you can probably find better, and at a lower price point.< /text>

None</pictures>

First time visiting this restaurant. We were looking forward to having some great seafood upon recommendation however were quite disappointed.  I had the bouillabaisse. The mussels tasted old, the lobster was overcooked, and the broth was bland.  The garlic toasts were also burned on the edges and was ruined with a cold red pepper spread.  My husband was very disappointed in the sea scallops, as they were also overcooked.   The cocktails, salad, clam chowder, and sourdough bread were great,  wish we had stopped there and called it a day.<//text>

< review>
The redesigned space transports the diner through the restaurant's history as you enter the first floor lobby then up the open spiral staircase to the main dining room. Staff are attentive and professional. The view is amazing from ANY table in the restaurant due to the tiered seating and levels of dining. The menu was spot on, fresh seafood focused. Though I went for the California organic grass fed steak cooked to perfection! Beer selection is out of sight, well tailored to the SD beer scene. The wine list was well stocked too. I'm going back!< /review>

< userid>
111383592478796555412<//userid>
<user_name>Francisco Meza</user_name><time>1407252776917<//time>< rate>
5</rate>
< Text>
I haven't been here for a while now, but I felt this place was worth leaving a good review.

There are very few places in San Diego that have a spectacular view like Tom Ham's Lighthouse. I used to come here more often.

You can sit outside on the balcony and have your dinner. Look at the menu online to get an idea of what they serve. I have never had anything here that wasn't good. HOWEVER, the last time I came (right after the remodel), the portions got smaller. I'm 6'1" tall and I had to order extra bread so I wouldn't leave the place hungry. The food is always great. I hate when I go to expensive restaurants and they server food I could make at home. This is not the case here.

Tom Ham's Lighthouse has started embracing the San Diego Micro Brew scene. You don't have to spend a lot of money to have a good time here. The bar itself is awesome to go to with your buddy. Bring a date, you can't go wrong.

I recommend the swordfish plate.</Text>

<time>1478537136208<//time><text>Here is a good example of a restaurant that remains in business just because of its location.
We took our friends for dinner to celebrate their wedding and out of a few choices, the bride picked Tom Ham's for the views hoping that the food would be good as well. To our disappointment it didn't live up to the hype of people's ratings and was in fact quite a letdown on most items.
Some of the starters were acceptable but not by far on the culinary level that their prices would suggest. ALL of the main courses were below average and the desserts were simply a slap in the face. Just as an example, the 'deconstructed" key lime pie had the texture of warmed up latex and was served with a side of bright green goo, that not only resembled but tasted like it was made by Monsanto. Another dessert - the whiskey cake (also deconstructed) honestly reminded me of Von's cake from a box that spent a few days in a refrigerator and was revived by microwave to be served to us, likewise with a side of their signature goo, this time in purple.
Bottom line, if you want to enjoy the view just get a bottle of wine with some snacks and save your money for a restaurant where they can actually cook food.</text>< Gmap_id>

105521418723750750555< /userid>
< name>
Carolyn Be</name>
< date>
1499111802106< /date>
< rate>
2< /rate>
<Review>We went yesterday for their Sunday brunch. It was my birthday, so I hoped to have a nice experience. It started out fine with the hostesses recognizing my birthday, we didn't have to wait (since we had reservations) and were given a table outside with a fabulous view. I have a feeling that they failed to tell our server about my birthday, because he didn't say or do anything.
Service: Our server didn't seem to want to wait on our table. There were only two of us at the table, so it's not like it was a large party.  He said he'd bring water, but we had to ask twice. He said he'd bring more sparkling wine, but we had to remind him. He didn't bring a bowl for the seafood shells, though all the tables around us had one. He let all the dishes pile up on the table, so I asked a hostess to have a busser come to the table (though nobody did). I finally had to ask the waiter to clear the table for us. He brought a birthday dessert to the table next to us, but didn't do the same for me. I saw multiple bussers out on the deck helping out, but they would keep passing our table. Instead of waiting on our table, our server was busy taking cell phone pictures for all the other guests, or talking with co-workers. He never asked if we wanted coffee when he saw us eating dessert. He only came back to the table to let us know it was "last call" and drop off the check.
Food: There were only a few lobster claws hidden beneath lots of stone crab claws. The two pieces of lobster were good, but the stone crab seemed off (shredded meat inside with zero flavor). There was a pasta station set up. I asked the guy what kind of pasta it was, and he said there wasn't any pasta. I assumed they ran out, but he gave no explanation. Of course when we were leaving the restaurant, I saw him cooking pasta for someone. The short ribs were greasy. I only saw blue cheese, not a platter with lots of options. There was a sign for whipped cream cheese to go with the desserts, but there was no whipped cream. The smoked salmon was good. The ricotta pancakes were delicious.
I realize that this place is a local institution with a fantastic reputation. The view and weather were great. I've been to tons of local buffets, casinos, hotels, resorts, Vegas, etc. This was such a bummer. Especially, on my birthday. It's possible our server was having a bad day, but I shouldn't have to make excuses for that. We felt ignored, were extremely disappointed, and won't be back. The server makes or breaks your experience. I assumed the tip was included in the check, and that's why he made no effort. But, thankfully it wasn't. Gratuity should not be taken for granted, or expected if all you do is pour a glass of wine and bring the check. There are hundreds of restaurants in San Diego to choose from. When you are paying $50 for brunch, you expect great service.
PS - I just saw another review for the same day we went. He only gave 2 stars also. Maybe we had the same server.< /Review>< Pics>
None</Pics>

<date>1528869968588</date><Rate>5< /Rate><GmapID>0x80deab0d284064d9:0xba249d609c190abe< /GmapID>< review>
Went there with our girlfriend for relationship anniversary dinner.

The place is beautiful and the view is wonderful! I highly recommand dining on the patio if you can, worth it and we were not cold. It was also very easy to park during week day.

The food was great. Maybe the soup was a bit salty to be a bit picky, but we were both really happy with what we ordered. The portion were also definitely enough and we had a hard time finishing!

Our waiter was delivering perfect service and was very nice. We were also offered a small chocolate cake as desert for our anniversary, really appreciated the attention!

Will defnitely come back and highly recommand :)</review>

<gmap_id>0x80deab0d284064d9:0xba249d609c190abe</gmap_id><user_name>Courtney Hartmann Tisa<//user_name><userid>114188782865605263874< /userid><Text>Hello, view! My friend and I came for lunch during Restaurant Week. It was first time and I enjoyed the charm of the building and the beautiful surroundings. It was a $15 lunch menu which included 2 choices of 3 courses. I chose the ceviche and the lobster roll.

The ceviche, while tasty, was different than others I had. It had kind of a gelatinous sauce that put me off at first, but tasted just fine. The lobster roll was a generous serving of two mini rolls stuffed full with lobster and a side of skinny fries.

We both ordered sangria ($10 each) and it was the perfect Friday afternoon meal. Our service was great. Our server answered several questions we had about the menu. I loved all the seafood choices and the view is definitely impressive.</Text><rate>5</rate>< Date>

<user_name>Clark Fogg<//user_name><gmapID>0x80deab0d284064d9:0xba249d609c190abe< /gmapID></record></dataset><record>
< user_id>
108100737183943161112< /user_id>
<username>Jorgeanne Cabuhat< /username><time>1418666450299< /time>< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< review>
Best brunch hands down.  If you want to impress visitors (i.e., parents) bring them here.  It not only has a great view of the bar and city skyline but the quality of food here is superb. Plus for $42 a person not that bad for the fanciness.

To be clear, it's $42 a person with unlimited everything including champagne, coffee, drinks, etc. You get scallops, mussels, snow crabs, and lobster claws, which are all pretty big and fat. They also have an omelet station, bacon, sausage, eggs benedict, waffles, pancakes, french toast, short ribs, pasta, and prime rib. Plus a station of all sorts of desserts. But I stuck with the seafood station for my first five plates.  They were just addicting. Favorite was the lobster claws. Easy to de-shell and delicious with dipper hot butter.

Staff are friendly and they are on top of making sure your drinks are filled, plates and buckets cleared, and napkins changed.

Tips: Make a reservation and either request a booth inside or seating on the patio for an even better view.</review>

<UserId.>105677799296219488516</UserId.>< username>
corrie noll<//username>
<Date>1504626925882< /Date><rate>4< /rate>< Text>
We celebrated a friends 90th Birthday on this dining experience!  We were pleased with everything the restaurant offered, from timely seating, reservation accommodations, our beautiful water-front seating!!, menue choices, the hostess, and our very friendly and attentive waiter!  The appetizers were amazing, the beer/cocktail selection was excellent, and our food was very good!  I am a very tough critic when it comes to food so if I were to critique anything on the cuisine I would say that the fish (I and my niece had the Market Fish, I believe was a Barramundi) was a bit over done and the falafel on the Vegetarian Dinner was a bit over fried and heavy, but aside from these issues both entrees were delish!
For starters, we had the calamari which was cooked perfectly and accompanied by a Honey Chili Lime Sauce to die for!  We also shared the mixed beet and greens also spot on-delish and Spanish Octopus with corn 3 ways, AMAZING! another noteworthy entree at our table was the Bouillabaisse, which I am looking forward to trying on my next visit!</Text>

< rate>
5</rate>
<Text>My wife and I went to Tom Ham's for our 25th anniversary. We wanted spectacular views and fantastic food, and we were well pleased. I started with the calamari (my standard) and it was delicious, not greasy though the sauce could have had more kick and zing for my taste. No biggie. My wife had the bluefin crudo, caught by the chef himself, so said the waiter. It was delicious, especially with the citrus bits. I had the diver scallops for the entree - beautifully cooked and super delicious. The melted leeks, crispy artichokes, Guajillo Grits, and Andouille Sausage all made for the perfect meal. My wife had the pan seared duck breast and it was to die for. It could have been rendered more, the skin more crispy, but omg it was delicious.

Now here's a funny thing. When we arrived we were wished happy anniversary, but apparently no one told our waiter. This wasn't a problem because he was super nice as it was and mentioning anything to him would have resulted in a free dessert like the folks behind us got, and we weren't there for a free dessert. I just am puzzled as to why the waiter wasn't told.

What's important is our overall experience, and we are still talking about the food. This was our third visit to San Diego, and first to Tom Ham's. Next time we go San Diego, we'll be going to Tom Ham's again, for sure!<//Text>< pics>

<userid>106801717568154343538< /userid>< username>
James J. Griffin< /username>
< time>
1448648410874</time>
< Rating>
4<//Rating>
< text>
I really like Tom Hamm's. We have our boat on Harbor Island so when I'm working down at the office aka the boat, lunches at Tom Hamm's are a must. Being a sailor, I really like that its an actual lighthouse, and the interior is decorated with old charts of the bay. You can really see what's changed over the years.

There's an impressive tap list, most all of which can be ordered in 4, 8, or 16 ounce pours.

The bartenders are also top notch. They really seem to care about what goes into the cocktails they're serving. The day shift often shows off what really goes into the later night's libations. You might even learn something.

The only spot Tom's falls down for me, especially for lunch, is a few of the dishes. The menu is a little small and a little expensive for the average daily lunch. But that's okay. The civiche is awesome, the steak frites are great, and the burgers are enormous. The burgers are probably a bit too big for me really.

One thing I will note, especially on the food, is when we had our rehearsal dinner, the food was amazing. All prefix menu options that don't show up on their regular menu as far as I'm aware. I had the swordfish which was spectacular.< /text>

< pics>

<UserId.>113568104056378423415</UserId.>< text>
The dining experience  in San Diego is complex and fraught with peril from the tourist traps in the Gaslamp to the joints in the East Village that put so much effort into being edgy and hip that they forget to produce great food.  In this culinary minefield is so refreshing to find a restaurant that has been a San Diego staple for many many years managing to delight the tastebuds and excite the senses.  We started with the chef's-choice dozen oysters which were extremely fresh and delightful.  I had a glass of wine while my beautiful wife tried the Sultry Sally cocktail which she thoroughly enjoyed.  The raw menu is not extensive but if our oysters were indicative it is fresh and well selected.  Moving on to some fried oysters we were astounded by the perfect counterpoint supplied by a dish of Asian inspired pickled vegetables.  My Shrimp and Grits was flavorful with fresh shrimp and nicely prepared grits and a little Andouille sausage to make it interesting.  My wife opted for the Whole Roasted Fish, sea bass. on the night we were there, perfectly roasted, presented with roasted peppers and a wonderful olive tapenade.  One of the best fish dishes I have ever eaten.  I finished off with the key lime pie  while my wife siped her second Sultry Sally.  The pie was more than the sum of its parts with the lime meringue providing a nice variation in sweetness while the sorbet broadened the palate of  tastes, temperatures and textures.  Lastly, I would be remiss if I did not mention our server, Jordan (the name is a coincidence), she did a great job looking after us and graciously listened to our endless prattle.  ONE OF THE BEST DINING EXPERIENCES WE HAVE HAD IN A VERY LONG TIME.<//text>
< name>
James Jordan<//name>

< Review>
This review is for their wedding services :
I had my magical and amazing wedding at Tom ham's lighthouse.
1) This places is has the amazing view of the ocean and San Diego skyline. They put in like millions of dollar of renovations and the new place is amazing. They custom build the ceremony site with a huge metal arch which is beautiful.
2) Our wedding co-coordinator was Stephanie and she was amazing, very prompt in replying to email and helped us in every step of the wedding planning. Some one here pointed out that tom ham's been not flexible which is not true, they were extremely flexible. Hey they allowed our dogs to be part of the ceremony which surprisingly a lot of other venues blatantly denied us to have our dogs being part of our ceremony on our special day.
3) The food is amazing . Ours was a mixed Indian-american wedding. The chef actually custom made all the appetizers in Indian style. the main entree was American-italian style and was really good.
4) We booked both the rooms and the price was very decent for ocean/city view venue in san diego.

This place has been everything I dreamed off for my wedding. I ddidnt have any complain. Kudos to the wedding managements.< /Review>

today was an embarrassmnt at lunch at the newly remodelled lighthouse.  The restaurent was busy with lots of tourists.  The food was terrible.  My fish and chips looked like a hot dog on a sick with a thick coating of greasy dough.  My chips were plentiful but cold/  there was nothing else on the plate but some condiments.  ther was no bread even to the two people in our party who had salads.  the crab Blt was served on thick slices of breatd that looked like morming French toast. We were all terribly disappointed at the terrible food served in such a beautiful setting.  Has any of your family tried the luncheon menu?  There certainly must be more palatable food that could be served to complement the SD view which is unsurpassed at the end of Harbor Island.

Christina Mason</username>

1409629993989< /Time>
<rate>5<//rate>< review>
Absolutely loved my experience here from the moment I walked in - it was a perfect  afternoon lunch with harbor views and our city skyline.  Linger at an outdoor table and watch the sailboats, kayakers, paddleboarders, and jetskis go by.  You can't beat the view.  I'm happy to have discovered this place, to now have another go-to spot to recommend to out of town guests.  I always recommended C-Level lounge for the views, and Tom Ham's is right up there.

They do have their own large parking lot with an abundant number of spaces.

They have a good selection of rotating craft beers, which can be purchased in 4oz, 8oz, or 16oz sizes.

My guest loved her Tuna Nicoise salad; I got to sample one of her hard-boiled eggs which tasted like it was marinated in red wine vinegar and cinnamon - so delicious. I ordered the fish & chips - perfectly battered crispiness. For dessert we tried the  gelato for $3.00/scoop.  The baily's gelato was refreshing.  Highly recommended lunch/brunch location.< /review>

<UserId.>112550892066956829081</UserId.>< username>
Christie Coats< /username>
< Time>
1410151222596< /Time>
< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< Text>
I absolutely love Tom Ham's. We went there tonight and sat in the bar area and had an amazing view of the downtown skyline. We ordered some oysters and other appetizers along with some of their speciality drinks. Their bartenders simply know how to make a drink. While they will make you anything you ask for, you can also ask them for a concoction that is all their own. Tonight we requested a mule, a Tiny Bubbles from their bar menu and asked the bartender to surprise us. He executed all three flawlessly and even wrote down the ingredients of the surprise drink for us.

For dinner we ordered several different types of oysters and shrimp. Unfortunately I am allergic to shellfish so while I didn't have any, everyone in the party said they were good. One of the food runners suggested some of his favorite oysters for the second round and the group said they were superior to the first oysters ordered. He specifically suggested the Luna which our group loved. I ordered the Peach and Burrata salad. I love buratta and will go out of my way to find places that serve it. The salad was amazing and had two huge pieces of burrata included. I will be ordering again the next time I am there. I also ordered the Shishito peppers; while they were good, there were a few that were very hot which I haven't experienced at other restaurants.

Overall, we love the view and the good drinks. The great food is just a fantastic bonus. While many of the other places closer to downtown don't have adequate parking, Tom Ham's has plenty of parking at the end of Harbor Island. We also got to see an amazing sunset over the parking lot as we were leaving. We will be back.< /Text>
